b"[![](../../cdshop/cdinfo.jpg)](../../cdshop/index.htm)  \n[Sacred Texts](../../index.htm)  [Hinduism](../index.htm)  [Index](index.htm)\n[Previous](sbe48524.htm)  [Next](sbe48526.htm)\n\n* * *\n\n9\\. And the subtle (body persists), on account of\n\np. 733\n\na means of knowledge, it being thus observed (in Scripture).\n\nThe bondage of him who knows is not, at that stage, dissolved, for this reason\nalso that the subtle body continues to persist.--How is this known?--Through a\nmeans of knowledge, viz. because it is thus seen in Scripture. For Scripture\nstates that he who knows, when on the path of the gods, enters into a colloquy\nwith the moon and others, 'he is to reply,' &c. (Kau. Up. I, 3 ff.). This\nimplies the existence of a body, and thence it follows that, at that stage,\nthe subtle body persists. The state of bondage therefore is not yet dissolved.\n\n* * *\n\n[Next: 10. Hence not in the way of destruction of bondage](sbe48526.htm)\n\n"